{"key":"post-8525518","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8525518</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Because manure or even coir/coffee has a better amount of nutes than berries and they contam easily so that is why they are used as a spawn and not a sub. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Actually, it's the exact opposite.&amp;nbsp; Grains have more 'nutes' than bulk substrates, and that's why grains are used as spawn.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The reason we don't mix various grains is because having a uniform grain size makes hydrating to the correct moisture content possible.&amp;nbsp; That's why rye berries and/or rye grass seed will outperform wild bird seed, which is a mix of different sized grains, some of which will be too wet, and others too dry.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;There is a lot of good to be gained from mixing various bulk substrate materials together, but not grains.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8525619</next>\n<prev>8525513</prev>\n<first>8524931</first>\n<last>8526025</last>\n<when>1213510437</when>\n<utime>06/15/08 09:13 AM</utime>\n</post>"}